1.title: Welcome + Structure of experiment
1.content:
Welcome to this study!


Before we begin please do the following:

  • Please maximize your browser window now so that it fills your entire screen
  • Switch off your phone/e-mail/music & anything else distracting
  • Please have your Prolific ID ready (It can be found in your account info)

Press the spacebar to continue

2.content:
This is the final question of the experiment

The audio recordings that you listened to in this experiment were NOT taken from a YouTube channel. Instead they were 'deepfaked' (i.e., we taught a computer program the way that a certain actor ('Chris') tends to speak and then had the program fabricate all the audio that you heard in the experiment; i.e., Chris never said any of the things you heard... it was actually the computer program 'speaking'.)

It is very important that you answer the following question honestly: ***When you were listening to the audio recordingings *** did you recognise that they were actually deepfakes?


Please click this in order to continue.

9.title: Instructions
9.content:
Instructions: Please read carefully


In this study we are interested in how people remember and react to what they hear online. You are going to listen to an audio recording extracted from a YouTube video. This audio is from a video of a person called Chris.

Please listen to the audio from Chris' video and pay close attention to what he says. We will ask you questions about this later on.
















Press the spacebar to continue.

11.title: Browser_note
11.content:
Warning on browser type

This study contains audio recordings. In the past, we have noticed that people using the "Brave" browser sometimes experience issues with audio. If you are currently using Brave browser, we kindly ask you to switch browsers before proceeding with this study, or (if you prefer not to use another browser) return the study on Prolific.

If you are using a different browser or have switched browsers already, you can press space in order to continue.

Press SPACE to continue.

19.title: Debriefing
19.content:
The study is now complete!

Below you will find an overview of what we were trying to investigate in this study. If you are not interested in this, you can immediately press the spacebar to exit the study.



So what was this study actually about? In this study we were interested in a topic called impression formation (i.e., how we come to like or dislike people that we meet for the first time). During the study you encountered an audio recording of a person (Chris) that was supposedly taken from YouTube. We actually created this audio ourselves

Half of the participants in the study encountered an audio recording where Chris said three positive things and two neutral things about himself. The other half of participants encountered an audio recording where Chris said three negative things and two neutral things about himself.

We then examined if what Chris said was enough to change people's first impressions of him. Specifically, would people in the first group like Chris while people in the second group dislike him? We tested this using self-report measures and a reaction time task. The former was designed to capture people's self-reported thoughts and feelings whereas the latter was designed to capture their more spontaneous or automatic reactions.

Afterwards we asked you to reflect on the experiment and tell us about your experiences with the task.

So that is it. We genuinely appreciate the time and effort you put into this experiment. Press the spacebar to complete the study.

25.content:
Informed Consent


Project Title: YOUTUBE AUDIO STUDY

Overview and Procedures: The purpose of this study is to examine how people remember and react to what they hear online. During the study you will listen to an audio recording taken from a YouTube channel. You will be asked to listen to this recording and remember what the person said. Afterwards you will be asked to answer some questions and take part in a reaction time task.

Risk and Benefits. This study involves no more risk to your physical or psychological health beyond those encountered in the normal course of everyday life. You may benefit by gaining a better understanding of psychological research. No other risks or benefits are anticipated.

Confidentiality. Any information obtained in this study will be kept strictly confidential and used solely for research purposes. We do not ask any identifying information and responses will be kept completely anonymous. Your anonymised data may be posted to a public repository for other researchers to make use of.

Compensation. You will receive a sum of money for participating.

Your Rights. Your decision to participate in this research is voluntary. You can withdraw from the study at any time without penalty. You do not have to answer any questions you do not want to.

Contact Information. If you have any questions or issues with this study please contact the principle investigator (Sean Hughes) at sean.hughes@ugent.be who can review the matter and provide further information.

You must be at least 18 years old in order to participate in this study.

Please indicate below whether you consent to participate in this research study. I declare that:

  • I have received information about the tasks and questions I will be asked during this research.
  • my participation in this scientific research is completely voluntarily.
  • I grant permission to the researcher to store, analyse, and report my results in an anonymous way.
  • I know that I can end my participation at each moment without having to give a justification.
  • I know that not participating or ending my participation has no negative consequences for me.
  • I know that I can receive a summary of the results of the research on demand.

metadata.title: S4_DF_DF_Audio
metadata.description: Study 4 examines if deepfaked audio recordings (similar to the audio from Experiment 3) is valenced, believable, and diagnostic of the actor's true nature.
